Before the likes of Au Pied de Cochon and Joe Beef hit the scene, chef Normand Laprise was the bold don of Montr√©al gastronomy. Many would argue he still is. His colorful edible art gains its greatest strength from unconventional pairings of fresh, local ingredients.
#TastingTable

Since 1976, this sleek restaurant across the street from March√© Jean-Talon has enticed diners with the tingle of sumac and pomegranate. The mouhamara and filet mignon in spicy terbialy sauce have reached cult status for a reason. #TastingTable

You might start your meal with seaweed "tapenalgue" or cheese, zucchini and grasshopper mousse, but this cheeky bistro is best known for its poutine flavored with house-made seal merguez. Order the wackiest delicacy on the chalkboard menu or settle in for a steak. #TastingTable

The homemade smoked meat, a north-of-the-border take on pastrami, has made this tiny deli a destination since 1928. Pair a sandwich with Colt's cherry cola, pickles and vinegary Montr√©al-style coleslaw--the ideal foil to the mouth-coating fat of the cured brisket.
#TastingTable

Much of the menu at this classic Romanian steakhouse has transformed little since its 1938 inception. That ice cream scoop of chopped liver may be presented with a modern, haute plating, but classics like verenikas and karnatzlach remain unchanged. #TastingTable

Portuguese-style grilled chicken carries serious cach√© in Montr√©al, and this casual spot is its most beloved purveyor. A mere $9.75 gets you fries, salad, rice and half of a juicy, marinated bird. A few dollars more will buy a pastry from the bakery, too.
#TastingTable

This is the place to taste the real, blue-collar Qu√©bec. Start the day with pancakes, eggs and the baked beans from which this greasy spoon gets its name. For lunch, there's traditional meat pie, meatball stew and smoked maple ham.
#TastingTable

Presentation is as important as taste at J√©r√¥me Ferrer's 13-year-old culinary jewel. A waiter with a cigar box presents not "just a cigar" but a cheese stick. Meals may end with a metal tree whose branches are filled with the likes of cotton candy and other homemade treats.
#TastingTable

Ever fantasized about the Paris Julia Child encountered in the 1950s? It breathes on at this 1956 bistro time capsule. Start with homemade rillettes or a cassolette of escargot--but remember that you must order a fluffy √Æle flottante. #TastingTable

One of the toughest reservations in town is this temple to excess. The chalkboard menu changes constantly, but standards, including an infernally indulgent lobster spaghetti, are worth pairing with surprises, such as cornflake-crusted eel nuggets. The same owners are also behind the neighboring Liverpool House and no-reservations wine bar Le Vin Papillon. #TastingTable

This tiny eatery can be hard to find, but its hand-pulled noodles are worth the search. They're made into meaty soups and spicy tangles of cucumber and beef. Don't miss the roujiamo, a dish of pulled pork on rice bread that traces its ancestry back to 1045 BC. #TastingTable

Chef Martin Picard helped catalyze the fatty, in-your-face ethos that defines nouveau Qu√©b√©cois cuisine. His empire now includes an out-of-town sugar shack and a roving food truck, but his flagship restaurant is still the only place to get classics including pig's head for two, foie gras poutin #TastingTable

The menu at this Old Port restaurant changes daily to showcase what's fresh and local. Venison--every part of it, from chops and sausage to tongue and heart--takes a special place on the bill of fare, alongside regional oysters.
#TastingTable

This beloved, 24\/7 poutinerie is perfect for a hangover breakfast, lunch or dinner. Go for the basic cheese-and-gravy fries or try La Fred Caillou, stacked with ground beef, smoked meat, spicy sausage and merguez.
#TastingTable

This 17th-century auberge was North America's first inn to receive a liquor license, back in 1745. Today the stonewalled rooms are home to a modern taste of New France, complete with a skilled sommelier.
#TastingTable

Dosas are central at Montr√©al's first South Indian restaurant. Large parties should order the six-foot paper dosa. There are numerous smaller options, too, as well as idli, uttapam, Indo-Chinese delicacies and an unforgettably lusty lamb biryani.
#TastingTable

Ethnically Korean, South American-bred chef Antonio Park is a Canadian celebrity for his Food Network appearances and his painterly way with sashimi. Order whatever the chef feels like plating. At brunch it might be a deceptively complex bacon-and-egg maki.
#TastingTable

Looking to indulge in bitter cocoa-marbled foie gras nougat alongside your oysters Rockefeller? The Ritz-Carlton, which once hosted one of Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton's weddings, spares no expense in pampering diners with delicacies new and old, √† la star chef Daniel Boulud.
#TastingTable
Cucumber Mint agua fresca w\/Gin!

The Montr√©al Gazette's Sarah Musgrave named this upstart her favorite new restaurant of 2014 for its marriage of Italian and Japanese aesthetics. The concept presents itself in the form of dishes, such as bucatini with pork confit, black garlic and soy. #TastingTable

The wines are all natural at this restaurant devoted to wild, indigenous food. Apps on the "peckish menu" might include raw bison served with trout lily and daisy leaves. Dessert follows the theme with fireweed panna cotta showered in larch sprouts.

#TastingTable
